<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n37009n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n37" href="#n37009n">N37 (VI.B.28A)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n37all.htm#n37009n"> 9(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 244 Indiarubber whale</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[<font size="-1">THE ART OF MONEY-GETTING</font>]</font>: In illustration <font color="green">[of his dictum than more persons are humbugged by believing too little than by believing too much]</font> <font color="green">[Barnum]</font> gave the instance of a Yankee lady who visted the museum to see the whales. Barnum knew her personally, and after she had watched the whales she called at Barnum&apos;s office. &ldquo;Mr. B., it&apos;s astonishing to what a number of purposes the ingenuity of us Yankees has applied india-rubber,&rdquo; she said. The <mark>whales</mark>, in her opinion, were constructed by Barnum of <mark>india-rubber</mark> and compelled to rise to the surface at regular intervals by means of a bellows puffing air into their bodies. <small> M.R. Werner, <a name="MRWP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MRWP"><cite title="source">P.T. Barnum</cite></a> (1923) 245</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
